TY  - JOUR
AU  - Schreft, Stacey L.
AU  - Smith, Bruce D.
T1  - The Effects of Open Market Operations in a Model of Intermediation and Growth
PY  - 1998
Y1  - 1998/07/01
DO  - 10.1111/1467-937X.00056
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 65
IS  - 3
SP  - 519
EP  - 550
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - This article presents a monetary growth model where spatial separation and limited communication create a role for banks. Monetary policy interacts with the financial system's liquidity provision to affect the existence, multiplicity, and dynamical properties of equilibria. Moderate levels of risk aversion and tight monetary policy can lead to multiple steady states. Dynamical equilibria can be indeterminate, with oscillatory paths. Thus financial market frictions are a source of indeterminacies and endogenous volatility. Under plausible conditions, tight monetary policy raises the nominal interest rate and inflation rate and reduces long run output. Thus, a central bank's liquidity provision can promote growth.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/1467-937X.00056
ER  - 



